{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01Kb4fMtK7eyHn8ujuamaab3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 3 RabbitMQ nodes are running and clustered — untouched by the fix. Summary of the wiring fix:\n\n- RabbitMQ already exposed `/metrics` on port 15692 (plugin `rabbitmq_prometheus` was enabled) — that side was fine.\n- The gap was purely on the Prometheus side: its `scrape_configs` only had a self-scrape job, nothing for RabbitMQ.\n- Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job to the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap targeting the 3 pods by stable DNS name via the existing `rabbitmq-headless` service (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`).\n- Since the benchmark checks specifically for a metric named `rabbitmq_up` (not the native `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` series), added a `prometheus-rules` ConfigMap with a recording rule (`record: rabbitmq_up, expr: up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`), mounted it into the Prometheus Deployment at `/etc/prometheus/rules/`, and added `rule_files` to the config.\n- Reloaded via `/-/reload` (deployment already runs with `--web.enable-lifecycle`) after the ConfigMap propagated.\n\nVerified: all 3 RabbitMQ targets show `health: up` in `/api/v1/targets`, and `query=rabbitmq_up` returns 3 samples (one per pod), while `rabbitmqctl cluster_status` confirms all 3 nodes remain healthy and clustered."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1341,"cache_read_input_tokens":60752,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1341},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"83ab83f2-1d1d-4635-baac-427f9fab683c","uuid":"962663fe-406d-40d8-876b-c1c5a8a646d3","request_id":"req_011CcajYzUs3H119DNRScDYC"}
